                                <p>09 Nov, 2017</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="inner-single-blog title-single-blog anim-elem">
                                <h1>Company Valuation Methods. Most Common Errors in Valuations (Part 8)</h1>
                            </div>
                            <div class="inner-single-blog image-single-blog anim-elem">
                                <img src="/upload/images/1510229632.jpg" alt="Company Valuation Methods. Most Common Errors in Valuations (Part 8)">
                                <div class="inner-image-one-post-ss"></div>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                        <div class="inner-single-blog desc-single-blog anim-elem">
                            <p><strong>Errors in the discount rate calculation and concerning the company&rsquo;s riskiness<br></strong></p>
<p>1. Wrong risk-free rate used for the valuation
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the historical average of the risk-free rate.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the short-term Government rate.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Wrong calculation of the real risk-free rate.
 </p>
<p>2. Wrong beta used for the valuation
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the historical industry beta, or the average of the betas of similar companies, when the result goes against common sense.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the historical beta of the company when the result goes against common sense.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Assuming that the beta calculated from historical data captures the country risk.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the wrong formulae for levering and unlevering the beta.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Arguing that the best estimation of the beta of a company from an emerging market is the beta of the company with respect to the S&P 500.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;When valuing an acquisition, using the beta of the acquiring company.</p>
<p>3. Wrong market risk premium used for the valuation</p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;The required market risk premium is equal to the historical equity premium.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;The required market risk premium is equal to zero.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Assume that the required market risk premium is the expected risk premium.
 </p>
<p>4. Wrong calculation of WACC
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Wrong definition of WACC.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;The debt to equity ratio used to calculate the WACC is different from the debt to equity ratio resulting from the valuation.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using discount rates lower than the risk-free rate.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the statutory tax rate, instead of the effective tax rate of the levered company.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Valuing all the different businesses of a diversified company using the same WACC (same leverage and same Ke).
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering that WACC / (1-T) is a reasonable return for the company&rsquo;s stakeholders.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the wrong formula for the WACC when the value of debt is not equal to its book value.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Calculating the WACC assuming a certain capital structure and deducting the outstanding debt from the enterprise value.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Calculating the WACC using book values of debt and equity.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Calculating the WACC using strange formulae.
 </p>
<p>5. Wrong calculation of the value of tax shields
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Discounting the tax shield using the cost of debt or the required return to unlevered equity.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Odd or ad-hoc formulae.
 </p>
<p>6. Wrong treatment of country risk
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Not considering the country risk, arguing that it is diversifiable.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Assuming that a disaster in an emerging market will increase the beta of the country&rsquo;s companies calculated with respect to the S&P 500.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Assuming that an agreement with a government agency eliminates country risk.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Assuming that the beta provided by Market Guide with the Bloomberg adjustment incorporates the illiquidity risk and the small cap premium.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Odd calculations of the country risk premium.
 </p>
<p>7. Including an illiquidity, small-cap, or specific premium when it is not appropriate
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Including an odd small-cap premium.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Including an odd illiquidity premium.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Including a small-cap premium equal for all companies.
 </p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Errors when calculating or forecasting the expected cash flows
 </strong></p>
<p>1. Wrong definition of the cash flows</p>
<p>-Forgetting the increase in Working Capital Requirements when calculating cash flows.<br></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering the increase in the company&rsquo;s cash position or financial investments as an equity cash flow.
 </p>
<p>2. Errors in the calculation of the taxes that affect the FCF.<br></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Expected Equity Cash Flows are not equal to expected dividends plus other payments to shareholders (share repurchases&hellip;)
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering net income as a cash flow.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering net income plus depreciation as a cash flow.
 </p>
<p>3. Errors when valuing seasonal companies<br></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Wrong treatment of seasonal working capital requirements.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Wrong treatment of stocks that are cash equivalent.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Wrong treatment of seasonal debt.
 </p>
<p>4. Errors due to not projecting the balance sheets<br></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Forgetting balance sheet accounts that affect the cash flows.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering an asset revaluation as a cash flow.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Interest expenses not equal to D Kd.
 </p>
<p>5. Exaggerated optimism when forecasting cash flows<br></p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Errors in the calculation of the residual value
 </strong></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Inconsistent cash flow used to calculate perpetuity.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;The debt to equity ratio used to calculate the WACC to discount the perpetuity is different from the debt to equity ratio resulting from the valuation.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using ad hoc formulas that have no economic meaning.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using arithmetic averages instead of geometric averages to assess growth.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Calculating the residual value using the wrong formula.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Assume that a perpetuity starts a year before it really starts.
 </p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Inconsistencies and conceptual errors
 </strong></p>
<p>1. Conceptual errors about the free cash flow and the equity cash flow
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering the cash in the company as an equity cash flow when the company has no plans to distribute it.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using real cash flows and nominal discount rates, or vice-versa.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;The free cash flow and the equity cash flow do not satisfy ECF = FCF + ΔD&nbsp;&mdash; Int (1-T).
 </p>
<p>2. Errors when using multiples<br></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the average of multiples extracted from transactions executed over a very long period of time.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using the average of transactions multiples that have a wide scatter.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using multiples in a way that is different to their definition.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using a multiple from an extraordinary transaction.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using ad hoc valuation multiples that conflict with common sense.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using multiples without using common sense.
 </p>
<p>3. Time inconsistencies<br></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Assuming that the equity value will be constant for the next five years.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;The equity value or the enterprise value does not satisfy the time consistency formulae.
 </p>
<p>4. Other conceptual errors<br></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Not considering cash flows resulting from future investments.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering that a change in economic conditions invalidates signed contracts.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering that the value of debt is equal to its book value when they are different.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Not using the correct formulae when the value of debt is not equal to its book value.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Including the value of real options that have no economic meaning.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Forgetting to include the value of non-operating assets.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Inconsistencies between discount rates and expected inflation.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Valuing a holding company assuming permanent losses (without tax savings) in some companies and permanent profits in others.</p>
<p>-Wrong concept of the optimal capital structure.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;In mature companies, assuming projected cash flows that are much higher than historical cash flows without any good reason.</p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Assumptions about future sales, margins, etc. that are inconsistent with the economic environment, the industry outlook, or competitive analysis.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering that the ROE is the return to the shareholders.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering that the ROA is the return of the debt and equityholders.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using different and inconsistent discount rates for cash flows of different years or for different components of the free cash flow.</p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using past market returns as a proxy for required return to equity.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Adding the liquidation value and the present value of cash flows.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Using ad hoc formulas to value intangibles.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Arguing that different discounted cash flow methods provide different valuations.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Wrong notion of the meaning of the efficient markets.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Applying a discount when valuing diversified companies.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Wrong arbitrage arguments.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Adding a control premium when it is not appropriate.
 </p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Errors when interpreting the valuation
 </strong></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Confusing Value with Price.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Asserting &laquo;the valuation is a scientific fact, not an opinion&raquo;.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;A valuation is valid for everybody.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;A company has the same value for all buyers.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Confusing strategic value for a buyer with fair market value.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Considering that the goodwill includes the brand value and the intellectual capital.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Forgetting that a valuation is contingent on a set of expectations about cash flows that will be generated and about their riskiness.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Affirming &laquo;a valuation is the starting point of a negotiation&raquo;.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Affirming &laquo;a valuation is 50% art and 50% science&raquo;.
 </p>
<p><br></p>
<p><strong>Organizational errors
 </strong></p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Making a valuation without checking the forecasts made by the client.
 </p>
<p>&mdash;&nbsp;Commissioning a valuation from an investment bank without having any involvement in it.</p>
<p>-Involving only the finance department in valuing a target company.</p>
<p><br></p>
<p>Other parts of the article &laquo;Company Valuation Methods&raquo; <a href="http://helicopter-view.com/blog/company-valuation-methods-part-1" target="_blank">(Part 1)</a>, <a href="http://helicopter-view.com/blog/company-valuation-methods-balance-sheet-based-methods-shareholders-equity-part-2" target="_blank">(Part 2)</a>, <a href="http://helicopter-view.com/blog/company-valuation-methods-income-statement-based-methods-part-3" target="_blank">(Part 3)</a>, <a href="http://helicopter-view.com/blog/company-valuation-methods-goodwill-based-methods-part-4" target="_blank">(Part 4)</a>, <a href="http://helicopter-view.com/blog/company-valuation-methods-cash-flow-discounting-based-methods-part-5" target="_blank">(Part 5)</a>, <a href="http://helicopter-view.com/blog/company-valuation-methods-basic-stages-of-a-valuation-by-cash-flow-discounting-part-6" target="_blank">(Part 6)</a>, <a href="http://helicopter-view.com/blog/company-valuation-methods-which-is-the-best-method-to-use-part-7" target="_blank">(Part 7)</a></p>
